06138nam a22007215i 9780774814874DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20092008xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748148747 a10.59962/97807748148742doi  a(DE-B1597)661965  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL186.5bE44 2008eb 7aPOL0080002bisacsh04a324/.0890097100aElecting a Diverse Canada :bThe Representation of Immigrants, Minorities, and Women /ced. by John Biles, Myer Siemiatycki, Erin Tolley, Caroline Andrew. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2009] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tReputation and Representation: Reaching for Political Inclusion in Toronto -- tDiversity and Elected Officials in the City of Vancouver -- tPolitical Representation of Minorities in the City of Montréal: Dream or Reality? -- tMore than Just Cowboys with White Hats: A Demographic Profile of Edmonton and Calgary -- tOur Unrepresentative but Somewhat Successful Capital: Electoral Representation in Ottawa -- tMany Faces, Few Places: The Political Under-Representation of Ethnic Minorities and Women in the City of Hamilton -- tRepresentation Deficits in Regina and Saskatoon -- tThe Patterning of Political Representation in Halifax -- tDiversity and Political Representation in Winnipeg -- tEthnoracial Minorities in the 38th Parliament: Patterns of Change and Continuity -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aElecting a Diverse Canada presents the most extensive analysis to date of the electoral representation of immigrants, minorities, and women in Canada. Covering eleven cities as well as Canada's Parliament, it breaks new ground by assessing the representation of diverse identity groups across multiple levels of government. The book begins by introducing the literature on electoral representation and the main concepts and frameworks underlying research on immigrants, women, and minorities. Using survey and census data, its chapters provide snapshots of officials elected at municipal, provincial, and federal levels, and compares these to portraits of the general population. The volume concludes by reviewing key findings and discussing patterns of over- and under-representation in Canadian government. Electoral representation is an important indicator of a democracy's health, yet there is limited research on how well elected representatives reflect the characteristics of voters. Electing a Diverse Canada provides a baseline for future research, not only by assessing electoral representation, but also by outlining key challenges impeding the future health of Canadian democracy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh1 aAndrew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrew, Caroline, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBiles, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiles, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBird, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Jerome H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBloemraad, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaverhill, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcea, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, Karen Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g